# iree-runtime-dist metadata

This is the iree-runtime-dist metadata for version @IREE_VERSION@ — a standalone, non-CMake
snapshot of the same enriched constants and JSON Schemas shipped inside the runtime tarball's
`share/iree-runtime-dist/`, packaged as a stable per-release asset so consumers who don't build
with CMake (or don't want to extract a multi-hundred-MB platform tarball just to read constants)
can fetch one small, version-pinned URL.

## File inventory

| File | What it is |
|---|---|
| `element_types.json` | `IREE_HAL_ELEMENT_TYPE_*` name → enriched properties object, generated from IREE's headers |
| `status_codes.json` | `iree_status_code_t` name → enriched properties object, generated from IREE's headers |
| `element_types.schema.json` | JSON Schema (2020-12) for `element_types.json` |
| `status_codes.schema.json` | JSON Schema (2020-12) for `status_codes.json` |
| `README.md` | this file |

## Encoding

Every element-type value is packed as:

```
value = (numerical_type << 24) | bit_count
```

Each `element_types.json` entry carries:

- `value` — the `IREE_HAL_ELEMENT_TYPE_*` integer constant
- `hex` — `value` formatted as `0x%08x`
- `numerical_type` — the IREE numerical-type enum name for `value >> 24`
- `category` — a coarse bucket derived from `numerical_type` (`opaque`, `boolean`, `integer`,
  `float`, `complex`, `unknown`)
- `signed` — `true` (signed), `false` (unsigned), or `null` (sign-agnostic / not applicable)
- `bit_count` — element width in bits (`value & 0xFF`)

Each `status_codes.json` entry carries:

- `value` — the `iree_status_code_t` ordinal
- `description` — an informational summary only, not a contract

## What you can and cannot depend on

The type **properties** in `element_types.json` — `value`, `hex`, `numerical_type`, `category`,
`signed`, `bit_count` — are authoritative: they are generated directly from the shipped runtime's
own headers, not transcribed by hand, and will always match the binary you paired this metadata
with.

What is **not** decided here is how those properties map onto *your own* native types. In
particular, choosing among `INT_*` (sign-agnostic), `SINT_*` (explicitly signed), and `UINT_*`
(explicitly unsigned) element-type families — and deciding what each maps to in your language or
runtime (e.g. an `INT_32` value into a signed vs. unsigned 32-bit host type) — is your integration
work. This metadata gives you the authoritative properties to make that decision correctly; it
does not make the decision for you.

## Schemas

`element_types.schema.json` and `status_codes.schema.json` are JSON Schema, draft 2020-12
(`"$schema": "https://json-schema.org/draft/2020-12/schema"`), and carry a `description` for every
field to document its meaning in-line — validate against them directly rather than re-deriving
field semantics from the data alone.
